"attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["English (Essex): apparently a habitational name from an unidentified place called in Old English <i>plega</i> ‘play, sport’ + <i>hyll</i> ‘hill’. Compare   Plaster   2."],"variants":[{"name":"Plaster","meanings":["English and North German: metonymic occupational name for a plasterer, from Middle English, Middle Low German <i>plaster</i> (from Latin <i>emplastrum</i> ‘(wound) plaster’ (originally a paste), from Greek <i>emplastron</i>, a derivative of <i>emplassein</i> ‘to shape or form’; the term was carried over into building terminology to mean ‘bonding agent’).","English: variant from a common pronunciation of <b>Plastow</b>, a habitational name from any of various places called Plaistow (in East London, Derbyshire, Sussex, and elsewhere), from Old English <i>plegestōw</i> ‘place where people gather for sport or play’. This can also be a variant of   Plaisted   (through interchangeable use of the Old English elements <i>stōw</i> and <i>stede</i>, both meaning ‘place’, in earlier times).","Jewish (Ashkenazic): from German <i>Pflaster</i> ‘(street) pavement’."]}]},{"name":"Thomas","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["New Testament name, borne by one of Christ's twelve apostles, referred to as ‘Thomas, called Didymus’ (John 11:16; 20:24). <i>Didymos</i> is the Greek word for ‘twin’, and the name is the Greek form of an Aramaic byname meaning ‘twin’. The given name has always been popular throughout Christendom, in part because St Thomas's doubts have made him seem a very human character."],"variants":[]}],"historicEvents":[{"id":1705191,"age":5,"year":"1315","toYear":"1317","julianDay":2201354,"title":"Famine Strikes Europe","description":"A famine caused by cold winters and wet summers across Europe caused millions to die due to starvation. Desperation from hunger caused high levels of crime, stampedes in bread lines in London, infanticide, and even cannibalism throughout Europe.","jurisdictionLevel":0},{"id":1705192,"age":18,"year":"1328","julianDay":2206102,"title":"First War of Scottish Independence","description":"The First War of Scottish Independence began after England invaded Scotland in 1296. The Treaty of Edinburgh was signed in 1328 which declared peace between the two kingdoms and brought the war to an end.","jurisdictionLevel":0},{"id":1705193,"age":27,"year":"1337","toYear":"1453","julianDay":2209390,"title":"The Hundred Years' War","description":"The Hundred Years' War between France and England was largely due to the question of legitimate succession to the French crown.","jurisdictionLevel":0}],"lifeSummary":"Thomas Playse was born in 1310, in Yorkshire, England as the son of William Playz and Alice De Nowers. He had at least 1 son and 1 daughter with Joan De Syggeson. He died in 1351, in England, at the age of 41."},"et":{"1310–1351":"1310–1351","1310–Female":"1310–Surnud","1330–1368":"1330–1368","1332–1370":"1332–1370","1295–1396":"1295–1396","–1369":"–1369","1330":"1330","1396":"1396","1351":"1351","1295":"1295","1370":"1370","1337":"1337","1315":"1315","1369":"1369","1368":"1368","1310":"1310","1453":"1453","1332":"1332","about 1332":"umbes 1332","1328":"1328","1317":"1317","Yorkshire, England":"Yorkshire, England","England":"England","Gristhorpe, Yorkshire, England":"Gristhorpe, Yorkshire, England"},"fi":{"1310–1351":"1310–1351","1310–Female":"1310–Kuollut","1330–1368":"1330–1368","1332–1370":"1332–1370","1295–1396":"1295–1396","–1369":"–1369","1330":"1330","1396":"1396","1351":"1351","1295":"1295","1370":"1370","1337":"1337","1315":"1315","1369":"1369","1368":"1368","1310":"1310","1453":"1453","1332":"1332","about 1332":"noin 1332","1328":"1328","1317":"1317","Yorkshire, England":"Yorkshire, England","England":"England","Gristhorpe, Yorkshire, England":"Gristhorpe, Yorkshire, England"},"fr":{"1310–1351":"1310–1351","1310–Female"